def build_model_1_1():
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Flatten(input_shape=(32,32,3)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(1024, activation='tanh'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='tanh'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='tanh'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer=tensorflow.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.00004),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Answer 1.3, Tune (4p)¶

  • Regularize the model. What works best?
    • Should consider batch normalization, dropout, l1/l2 regularization (or Nesterov)
  • Tune other hyperparameters (e.g. learning rate, batch size,...) as you see fit.
    • At least consider tuning learning rate, ideally also momentum, decay, other optimizers
  • Explain your findings and final design decisions. Discuss the results.
    • Should be better, at least it shouldn't overfit
I added BatchNormalization right before every dense layer and optimized layers' kernel with l2 optimizer. This should reduce overfitting issues. I chose to increase gradually the dropout after each dense layer. It forces deep layers to regularize more than the top layers. Adam optimizer now performs well with a high learning rate and smaller decay rate. The number parameter didn't change. Overall the model is stable, does not overfit and achieves 88% of accuracy  (length: 468)

Max val score: 87.52%

def build_model_1_3():
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Flatten(input_shape=(32,32,1)))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.Dense(1024, activation='tanh', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='tanh', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='tanh', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer=tensorflow.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001, decay=1e-10),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Answer 2.1, ConvNet (7p)¶

  • Build a sequential ConvNet, get at least 90% accuracy.
    • Conv2D layers, input shape (32,32,1)
    • Consider using blocks of Conv2D layers with maxpooling in between
    • Use zero-padding in Conv2D layers because the images are small
    • At least one dense hidden layer and dense output layer (sigmoid)
    • Consider adding batch normalization, dropout
    • Consider small dropout rates in beginning, larger dropout rates later in network
    • Consider other optimizers and tuning learning rate, momentum,...
  • Explain what you did and why (800 chars). Is it working well?
    • Should be quite elaborate and sensible
As a CNN learns faster and smoother than dense models I reduced the total number of parameters to be learned. I chose to add 4 couples of conv layers with increasing complexity and a Dense layer for the classification task. As seen before, I added BatchNormalization after and L2 regularization to reduce overfitting issues. I kept the same Dropout setting strategy (increase dropout after every couple of conv layer) as it lets the network to regularize parameters better. Within this setting the relu activation function performs better than the tanh activation function. Overall the network performs well. It doesn't overfit and achieve 95% of accuracy. The model performed way better with a high batch size and lower learning rate  (length: 736)

def build_model_2_1():
  model = models.Sequential()
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(32, 32, 1), kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
  model.add(layers.Flatten())
  model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  model.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
  model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax', kernel_regularizer=tensorflow.keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.compile(optimizer=tensorflow.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.00005),
                loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

Answer 2.2, Data Augmentation (3p)¶

  • Augment the preprocessed training data.
    • Use small variations (small shifts up-down, left-right) of flips becasue the images are small

As we want to classify numbers, in my opinion, image flipping and rotation didn't suit the problem. Moreover, Image shifts seemed to decrease the model performance. After checking misclassified data, I chose to add random zooming and 'nearest' as fill mode. It increased the performance by a factor of 0.6%.  (length: 309)

Answer 3.3, Class activation map (4p)¶

  • Show a class activation map for your last convolutional layer
  • Superimpose the activation map over the image, or plot side by side
    • Should make sense, detect interesting regions to classify the number
def plot_activation_map():
  tensorflow.compat.v1.disable_eager_execution()

  model = load_model_from_file(base_dir, 'model_2_2')
  image = rgb2gray(X_test)[0]

  # We add a dimension to transform our array into a "batch"
  # of size (1, 32, 32, 3)
  x = np.expand_dims(image, 0)
  preds = model.predict(x)

  #output class
  argmax = np.argmax(preds)
  output = model.output[:, argmax]

  last_conv_layer = model.get_layer('conv2d_31')

  #gradient
  grads = K.gradients(output, last_conv_layer.output)[0]
  pooled_grads = K.mean(grads, (0, 1, 2))
  iterate = K.function([model.input], [pooled_grads, last_conv_layer.output[0]])
  pooled_grads_value, conv_layer_output_value = iterate([x])

  for i in range(256):
    conv_layer_output_value[:, :, i] *= pooled_grads_value[i]

  heatmap = np.mean(conv_layer_output_value, axis=-1)
  heatmap = cv2.resize(heatmap, (image.shape[1], image.shape[0]))

  #visualize activation map
  heatmap = np.maximum(heatmap, 0)
  heatmap /= np.max(heatmap)
  return heatmap

def build_model_4_1():
  vgg16 = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(32, 32, 3))

  for layer in vgg16.layers:
    if(layer.name in ['block5_conv1', 'block5_conv2', 'block5_conv3', 'block4_conv1', 'block4_conv2', 'block4_conv3', 'block3_conv1', 'block3_conv2', 'block3_conv3']):
      layer.trainable = True
    else:
      layer.trainable = False

  model = tensorflow.keras.models.Sequential()
  model.add(vgg16)
  model.add(tensorflow.keras.layers.Flatten())
  model.add(tensorflow.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
  model.add(tensorflow.keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))


  model.compile(optimizer=tensorflow.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.000001),
                loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

def store_embeddings(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
  """ Stores all necessary embeddings to file
  """
  model = load_model_from_file(base_dir, 'model_4_1')
  model = tensorflow.keras.models.Sequential(model.get_layer('vgg16'))

  train_features = model.predict(X_train, verbose=1).reshape((X_train.shape[0], 512))
  test_features = model.predict(X_test, verbose=1).reshape((X_test.shape[0], 512))

  store_embedding(train_features, 'train_colored_images')
  store_embedding(test_features, 'test_colored_images')
